SIMPLE: indurate
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Indurate
<hw>In"du*rate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>induratus</ets>, p. p. of <ets>indurare</ets> to harden. See
<er>Endure</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Hardened; not soft; indurated.</def>
<rj><au>Tyndale.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Without sensibility; unfeeling; obdurate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Indurate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Indurate
<hw>In"du*rate</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Indurated</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Indurating</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To make hard; <as>as, extreme heat
<ex>indurates</ex> clay; some fossils are <ex>indurated</ex> by exposure
to the air.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To make unfeeling; to deprive of sensibility; to
render obdurate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Indurate</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Indurate
<hw>In"du*rate</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To grow hard; to harden, or
become hard; <as>as, clay <ex>indurates</ex> by drying, and by
heat</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Indurated</ent>⟦br⟧
